Inflation in Europe has dropped on food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, the price increase in the 13 countries of the euro area was higher than forecast, after an inflation rate of 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 percent was recorded, the European Community statistics office located in Luxembourg said.
Official forecasts indicated only 3 percent, Bloomberg said.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the guiding interest rate by saying that the decrease in interest, with the rise in commodity prices and the decline in unemployment, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two percent.
According to an analyst, this is the Catch 22 for the ECB: “We need to deter” inflation in order to no longer have to intervene on this subject later.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 percent is a record over the past twelve years and in Spain, it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has taken off due to rapidly rising food and energy prices.
Grain futures market odds have increased by 88 percent and soybean price has also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased considerably in 2007.
This year, the global oil price rose 52 percent, and last month, a barrel of black gold cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008 the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 this year to 2.5 percent but in 2009 it will drop to 1.9.
According to analysts, the inflation rate over 12 months remains around 3 percent, however, in the next 3 to 4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to lower the guideline rate twice in 2008.
Gallup indicates a government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of Fidesz (Alliance of Young Democrats) has increased significantly in early December, so since 2002 it has had the largest number of supporters, while Gallup (survey institute) has never seen such low socialist support, i.e. 13 per cent.
For loyal voters, the difference would represent, due to the greater determination of the opposition voters, more than two-thirds (71 percent) of support against a fifth (20 percent) of support for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the poll, the MDF (Hungarian Democratic Forum) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the parliamentarians’ threshold: their support is 2% among the entire population.
Of the loyal voters certain to go to vote, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate has continued to deteriorate from the previous lower point, the proportion of those who considered the country's economic situation to be particularly serious has never been so high, rising to 41 per cent and according to complementary 46 per cent the situation is fairly serious.
After the more optimistic outlook of last spring and summer, families are again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For next year, the majority of the population expects a worsening and only a tenth expects an improvement in the situation.
Last December, 71 percent of those surveyed, a majority never seen in Gallup’s previous polls, judged the Prime Minister was doing his job rather badly than well.
13 percent of respondents trust or have great confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54% do not trust the Prime Minister at all and 27% the Fidesz president.
One indicator of the change in the political situation is the proportion of society thinking that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister can be dealt with without changing government.
While after the riots in October last year, 35 per cent of respondents wanted the government and the prime minister to remain in office, this rate currently represents only 20 per cent. The relative majority (33 per cent) believe that holding new elections would be the solution to this situation.
When asked about the intention to vote, 60 percent of respondents said they would definitely vote and the complementary 20 percent said they would probably vote.
To make the comparison, for a "legislative election to be held next Sunday", only 55 percent of respondents would certainly participate and 15 percent would likely participate.
74 per cent of people would say no to enrolment fees in higher education, 79 per cent would say no to consultation fees and 84 per cent would say no to hospital stay fees.
When we look only at the same proportions among those who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, respectively 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital stay costs.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by nearly twenty percent
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs commercial triangle maintained the average price increase of 16 percent last year, compared to the difference that the VAT rate did not increase this year.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (Daily Economy)
This year, in the Budaörs commercial triangle, the usual daily Christmas basket also increased by 16 percent on average, with a value increase significantly greater than a thousand Forints shown in all hypermarkets.
Prices, "which had already flown" in grocery stores last December, have no longer increased sharply compared to the previous high base.
Nevertheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased significantly below nine thousand Forints last year now cost more than ten thousand Forints.
The daily basket in the hypermarkets surveyed exceeded the psychological threshold of at least 91 Forints of ten thousand.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 Forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 Forints.)
Prices of Unicum and living fish remained almost at last year's level, but prices for turkey, nut and poppy rose sharply.
In stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics), but, at Auchan, one kilogram of bread was found at only 139 Forints.
Competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 Forints.
It was amazing to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the recorded two-liter bottle of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints the recorded bottle included.
However, this year, in terms of daily basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of its daily basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased it by about 18 and 18 percent respectively.
By comparing the most expensive basket of last year and the cheapest basket of this year, we see a 12 percent gap while the difference between the cheapest of last year and the most expensive of this year is 21 percent.
Prices increased by an average of 1,480 Forints.
Last year, prices rose by an average of 1,206 Forints, while knowing that the impact of the increase in the VAT rate was already noticed in last year's Christmas prices.
This process confused trade, as hypermarkets could not clearly determine what margin to apply to products as they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, he is likely to lose a large profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
Due to the change in the VAT rate, the rise in the price of the daily basket evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was 1,720 forints higher than that of 2006, while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive since the value of the most expensive basket was 1,630 Forints higher than last year and the prices of the cheapest also increased by 1,284 Forints.
By bringing the two Christmas seasons closer together, we saw a catastrophic rise in prices, in less than 20 months the prices of daily consumption items increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH data: for some necessity feeds, the Institute of Statistics observed a price increase of more than 30 per cent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, for flour and egg.)
According to the Daily Basket of the latter, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, has increased by just over 10 percent from the base.
According to the indices, flour suppliers hold a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have managed to accept the abrupt price increases also by multinationals.
In the commercial gold triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
According to our experiences, most customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take long-term foods by pallets.
On Wednesday morning important tails were trained at the boxes of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, revenue is less in the province, many multinationals complain to survey companies that they do not even reach the expected revenue, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer goods.
Many hospitals save on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by improper use of antibiotics, have been registered in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, overwork of medical personnel do not help block infections, says the chief doctor of the National Center for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals also save on disinfectants
Not long ago an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the traumatology department of the János Hospital.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria were detected in a man hospitalized following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured in a serious car accident left the hospital but soon after he had to return because of an MRSA infection and, since then, doctors have not been able to do a major surgery because of the bacteria found in his body.
Until December 10 of this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multiresistant pathogen were reported to the National Nosocomial Monitoring System, said Karolina Böröcz, chief doctor at the National Center for Epidemiology.
That is, the number of infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogen that has actually been registered in hospitals and for the rest we don't have any information.
Approximately two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. by methicillin-oxacillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
One-third of people are carrying Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing any disease.
Infections caused by SAs (such as anginas, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) react well to antibiotics, they are easily curable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacterium, which reacts well to antibiotics, will develop a well-resistant bacterium that will proliferate rapidly in poor hospital conditions.
In the event of provisional or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium can cause serious hospital infections, such as a traumatic infection or sepsis, in elderly patients, small weights or with a weakened body.
According to the director physician of the János Hospital, there is nothing special in MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily life of hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the outbreak, we do not find MRSA just the one we are not looking for, said Tibor Nyulasi.
The SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
“These patients are isolated, the caregivers wear rubber gloves and protective masks and we have appropriate antibiotics to treat them,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they are carrying MRSA, however the infection cannot always be prevented.
Sampling is not fashionable
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented but the current conditions and circumstances in Hungarian hospitals are not favorable to prevent the development and proliferation of multiresistant pathogens, Karolina Böröcz says.
As this infection is mainly manifested in hospitals and elderly residences, hospitals should monitor hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients carrying MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not finance these exams.
Most cases only appear if the MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, the chief physician of the epidemiological center said.
The European Union has stringent recommendations on the proper use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are Hungarian guidelines for the healing of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
The realization of microbiological samples is even more rare in outpatient and basic care, said Karolina Böröcz.
Many hospitals save on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical staff.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, put on gloves and protective masks, but important gaps are detected in hospitals also in this area.
MRSAs proliferate by infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and by contact, however, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other, while in terms of an epidemic, the sick should be at least 1.5 meters away from each other.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in a difficult financial situation, save on disinfectants, lack of nurses, many sick, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures are followed, the number of infections is lower in a demonstrable manner or the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government Project Against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant expenses for social security funds, which is why we fight this infection everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has prioritized the prevention of the incidence of multiresistant pathogens (such as MRSAs) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The commissioner, the perpetrator of a deadly accident, was not in a state of drunkenness.
The official statement concerning the fatal accident caused by the 22nd district commissioner has been drawn up.
It can be excluded that the 22nd district commissioner, who has since resigned from his position, who crushed a pedestrian by causing his death last Tuesday, would have drove in a state of drunkenness or dizziness, said Attila Morvai, a spokesman for the capital’s public prosecutor’s office after the relative finding was established.
The finding confirmed the first result of the investigation, which has already found that the former Commissioner had not consumed alcohol before getting to the wheel.
Last Tuesday, the former chief of the police station of the 22nd district crushed a 55-year-old man who stood in front of him when he turned, with his personal car, in the street Kossuth Lajos of the 22nd district. The man wanted to cross the road, not passing the pedestrian crossing.
(Moreover, the fact that he was crossing the road outside the pedestrian passage does not constitute a mitigating circumstance, according to the Road Code a car that starts a turn must let pedestrians pass.)
The pedestrian died after being transported to the hospital.
Following this accident, the Commissioner resigned from his position and asked for retirement because, according to the police communication, this accident has greatly disturbed him.
The investigation is conducted by the Budapest Prosecutor’s Office.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former Commissioner initially cooperated with the magistrates responsible for conducting the investigation.
Additional €400 million for infrastructure
Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), Marta Gajecka, signed three agreements worth €400 million in a credit line to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure as well as energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of €300 million for the Hungarian budgetary financing of transport and environment projects to be implemented from the Cohesion Fund, with a loan contract worth €100 million already signed by the parties. This time, the signed contract concerns the use of the remaining €200 million.
The €150 million credit agreement also covers the budgetary financing of educational projects.
The EIB has approved a total of €300 million for Hungary, the remaining €150 million can be used later, following the extension of the credit contract.
The parties have signed a €50 million contract for innovation, the state budget will use this envelope in the first place as part of the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
During the negotiations, the project of Metro Line 4 was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would re-discuss any change to the original contract when Hungary finalized details of the financing of the metro with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has allocated a total of €8.4 billion to finance 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB grants its credits to EURIBOR in accordance with the interest rate, with an 8-year grace period and no commitment fee.
Bulgaria, the paradise of the EU real estate market
The evolution of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of all of Europe is turned to this country of the Balkans little mentioned in the past.
What, or and who bought in this EU market that is always the cheapest but who will quickly become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
Currently, in real estate, Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most trendy target in Eastern Europe with its cheap ski apartments and seaside houses.
In the mountains, the most popular regions are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albena, the "Golden Sands", the "Sun Coast", the former Sozopol and Nessebar but they are increasingly looking for a building in the region of Kavarna and Balcik as well.
According to analysts at Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later, the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also awaken the interest of investors and they are also increasingly buying in the very cheap corner of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, also offers attractive opportunities, with shops and office areas promising the highest amortization rate.
Bulgaria is on the best path to become one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe and thus be a priority destination, after the summer and winter seasons, also in the other two seasons of the year.
More vigilant investors are already buying in large numbers, for example in the corner of Bansko.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria are looking at the same time to change their lives, their way of life.
Most buyers are English but others come from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. On the banks of the Black Sea and in the most renowned ski resorts, we traditionally meet many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who intend to settle buy renovated buildings, at a price ranging from 50 to 100 thousand euros, or old decayed houses, at a price ranging from 5 to 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication possibilities, the proximity of a large city, shops and in general that of the local doctor.
The second group includes buyers of secondary homes (since last December Bulgaria has been listed among the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group consists of commercial investors who buy in the hope of achieving medium- or long-term added value.
The price of buildings in the capital is constantly rising as a result of increasing demand.
In the European Union, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria, however, in the last 5 years, they have increased by 21 percent each year.
The rise in real estate prices essentially exceeds the rise in wages.
Fodor and the six percent Hungarians
According to the communication of Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, the meetings of the professionals will end on Tuesday, however, Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of the ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Roadmap to define efforts to be made after the emissions reduction period defined by the Kyoto Protocol until 2012.
Currently, there are intense discussions on this issue between developing countries and developed countries.
The United States also reported that, for the time being, it did not want to discuss exact figures, although it was prepared to sign an agreement on reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 25 to 40 percent from 1990 levels until 2020.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries commit themselves, except for reducing emissions, to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also signed on aid to developing countries.
The Kyoto Protocol support fund will be managed by a board of 16 members likely under the United Nations Global Environment Fund (GEF), Piac es Profit (Market and Profit) said.
Six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Minister of Environment and Water Gábor Fodor confirms the ambition of the EU to maintain its role as a flagship in global efforts to protect the climate and encourage the signing of the new international agreement before 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU would undertake to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020 from the level reached in 1990, regardless of the successful signing of the “After 2012 Agreement,” and was willing to reduce them by up to 30 percent if other major regions of the world and/or developing countries were also ready to make commitments and accountability-adjusted.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997, the countries signatory to the Kyoto Protocol had targeted a 5.2 percent reduction in total and all of the 15 EU members at that time took the commitment by 8 percent less.
Hungary has undertaken to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to the period between 1985 and 1987, our country will fulfill its commitment, the Ministry of the Environment's press release recalls.
The challenge is great in Bali because the long-term international agreement on climate policy must be put in place within two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be pushed back after 2012. In this case, the commitments to reduce below the values set forth in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new scientific international emission reduction system, the need of which was highlighted in the new IPCC report.
The reduction in emissions would be delayed and the rise in Earth's average temperature of more than 2 degrees Celsius could no longer be avoided, which scientists say would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
The British Army Recruits on YouTube
The units of the British army communicate, on the video sharing site, recordings made during its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan with the aim of becoming popular.
First, it is the British Air Force (RAF) that has become passionate about YouTube: special units in Afghanistan are uploading videos of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC announced.
These recordings, taken using miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are controlled at the Air Force Operations Headquarters in Kandahar and are then transferred to Londres or the compatriots upload them to the Internet.
The political message is indispensable
Air Force soldiers have already spent 139 sequences on the net through this route and their "chain" has been watched by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered as the "defenceheadquarters" in spring 2007 and communicated videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Office and the International Peacekeeping Forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own YouTube channels.
Mission in Afghanistan
According to the air force's initial goal, the videos were passed on the net to recruit and, according to the Ministry of Defense, they were also used to make the public aware of the actual goals of the military's presence abroad.
The propaganda published in this way costs virtually nothing compared to the usual recruitment advertisements on television, according to defense consultant Gordon Mackenzie, but it also inevitably carries a political message because it in a special form justifies the validity of the military operations decided by the government.
The Americans played a game
The army is bothered because, apart from the composed and carefully censored videos, amateur videos have been passed onto the sharing site which also show, for example, the deaths of soldiers: in “official” propaganda films, somewhat hypocritical, officers do not avoid talking about the losses but they never show the bloody side of the fight.
Indeed, many videos had already been broadcast on the net showing the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were being carried out on a real mission, but the British army has only recently been busy uploading these videos.
The Americans recruit a little differently by using the downloadable America's Army shooting game for free. In this game the player can directly place the soldiers as part of a more or less real simulation.
