Mega strike forces gather
The unions of the League and the National Association of Workers' Councils will constitute on Friday their strike committee to coordinate Monday's indefinite strike.
On Saturday, a general protest assembly will be held and on Monday, on the day of the final vote on the health funds law, the strike will begin.
This action will certainly cause significant stops in traffic as rail traffic will be stopped almost totally and employees of BKV (the public transport company) will also strike until 13:00.
The league's unions will announce on Friday afternoon the details of their Monday strike, organized with the National Association of Workers' Councils.
The LIGA - MOSZ strike committee will also be formed, it will serve as a coordinator of Monday’s actions.
On Saturday, a general protest assembly will be held and, starting Monday, organizations joining the strike will stop work for an indefinite period if they fail to reach an agreement with the government.
This means that the date of the end of the strike, starting from the day of the vote in parliament on the health funds law, is not defined.
If the National Assembly does not adopt the health funds law, the unions will immediately withdraw the call for strike.
On the other hand, if the law is passed, the strike committees will meet and decide on what to take.
According to the national assembly's Monday agenda, it is likely that the vote on the health funds law will only take place late in the evening or even at night.
Due to the strike scheduled for Monday, significant stops are planned in traffic: railways will stop work for an indefinite duration and in the morning part of public transportation in Budapest and more than half of Volán companies are at risk of being stopped.
At the same time, at different points in the country, half of the track will also be blocked.
Many unions and civilian organizations have joined the call for strike, the list of which is constantly updated on the League's website.
Some organizations report striking for an indefinite duration, others declared a temporary stoppage.
Until Thursday afternoon the MÁV (Hungarian Iron Chemists) and the Free Railroad Trade Union (VDSZSZ) have failed to reach an agreement on minimum services, and, as Christmas holidays approach, more and more people are taking the train.
According to current communications, public transport in Budapest will strike from the start of service until 1 p.m., the airport in Budapest between 7 a.m. and 9 a.m., the Industrial Trade Unions of Electricity and Thermal Energy of the League will strike four hours, the Trade Union of Professors and the Democratic Trade Union of Professors will strike two hours, respectively.
The National Association of Physicians will alternately strike across the country, while the Health and Social Sector Employees Union (EDDSZ) attached to the SZEF will make a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands made by the League requires that the government withdraw its proposal for health reform and submit a new concept to social debate.
The second claim requires that the new method of calculating the retirement to be implemented from next year be introduced in several stages.
The third claim calls for a guarantee of retirement before the legal age, which would allow the functions that deserve it to be put into the system before 2010.
The fourth reason for the action is the rejection by the Free Train Trade Union (VDSZSZ), attached to the Trade Unions of the League, of the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport concerning secondary railway lines and the waiting for another proposal.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard has increased country risk
According to the Political Capital Risk Analysis Division, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, established last August, with the support of Jobbik Magyarországért Mozgalom (Movement for Better Hungary), increase the political risk of Hungary and the region in several aspects.
In its “risk warning,” the company notes that, in connection with the Hungarian Guard’s activity, the greatest political risk is already that “short-term aggressive ethnic clashes can occur as a result of the already existing ethnic tension between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy population of Hungary.”
The research institute added that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy aimed likely to cause this situation is the main reason.
As they say, this is explained by one of the main gaps of Hungarian political actors: "public actors have passed the public debate on the Roma affair to representatives of radical and extreme political groupings that have based a political strategy on the dispute between the Gypsies and the Hungarians."
The problem is aggravated, normal dialogue becomes impossible, extremists are strengthened and the arrival of aggressive conflicts is more likely, they say.
However, according to the research institute, under the effect of the increased attention of the Hungarian and international media, the activity of the Hungarian Guard "has significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, in particular with regard to the confidence in the stability and democratic maturity of the country."
They recall that, following greater publicity given to the reorganization of the Hungarian radical and far-right groups since the autumn of 2006, many associations have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007 giving themselves the name of "National Self-Defense Association".
“The common trait of these gatherings is that they define themselves as a civilian organization as they publicly declare the preparation of their members for defence missions (disasters, national defence, defence of order), armed, if necessary, in addition to referring to the incapacity of the police, the army, in other words of the state,” they added.
They reported that everything was going through the method that, based on the resentment of politics and party society, seeks to disguise different political ambitions from a civil aspect.
The emphasis on civility and the status of association therefore serves only to avoid the legal traps of registration of these associations in the court, but they are also a political strategy.
The analysis indicates that the activity of the Hungarian Guard is a factor that also increases the risk in relation to neighborhood relations.
“In recent months, many neighboring countries have cited the Hungarian Guard as a potential source of risk and the ultranationalist political actors in some neighboring countries want to justify their anti-Hungary policy by referring to the constitution of the Hungarian Guard.
This influences the political stability of the region,” they added.
According to the research institute, the constitution of the Hungarian Guard is not a unique phenomenon in Eastern Central Europe, political risks have increased across the region as a whole.
As they say, the operation of the Hungarian Guard resembles, for example, the activity of the Bulgarian National Guard whose constitution was declared by the Bulgarian National Union (UNB) in August 2007.
The many Roma riots that broke out in a neighborhood of Sofia (Kraszna Poljana) were the sources of the constitution of the Bulgarian guard.
