In Hungary, the law exactly defines holidays and, around the holidays, it has become common to reorganize working days whose number will decline next year.
The holidays are not uniform in the EU and the United States either.
Hungarian legislation distinguishes national and state holidays as well as rest days.
Rest days are often linked to religious holidays or important historical events.
In Hungary, we celebrate the New Year, the last day of the year that ends and the first day of the New Year are also days of rest, the latter especially so that the wake-upers can rest quietly.
In one year, we have 11 holidays marked in red.
March 15 is a national holiday, in commemoration of the revolution of 1848, as is October 23, which is the commemorative day of the revolution of 1956.
On August 20, we celebrate the constitution of our state, on May 1st is Labour Day, and on November 1st and 2nd, we remember our family members and our deceased friends.
In addition, we have two days on Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
The days of our state, national or even religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, according to the calendar, it has become common to reorganize working days in cases where there is only one working day left before or after the holiday marked in red.
It is true that we pay the price of extended weekends by working or going to school on the Saturday before the extended weekend.
For many years, the Minister of Labour has decided in particular regulations on the days of replacement of the days before or after the holidays.
The law extends to all employers and their employees, to public servants and to those working in the public service.
However, it does not apply to service companies, institutions turning uninterruptedly and in service, by their vocation, and also for days of rest.
This year, the working days will be changed only around the holidays of the year: starting on December 24, life stops almost all over the country because, according to experiences, the majority of people rather spend overtime or take vacations that they have saved for these purposes so that they can spend the days between Christmas and New Year's Day at home.
Next year a lot of holidays fall in the middle or end of the week, so there will be fewer changes in working days compared to this year.
The calendar will be reorganized for the first time around the Labour Day to allow employees to stay at home four days in a row.
Saturday, April 25th will be a working day to have a day of rest on Friday, May 2.
