"This approach tends to address the major problems of the economy, namely the growing lack of free capital that banks could lend," wrote Bernard Baumohl of Economic Outlook Group.
“Central banks’ concerted action has reduced the likelihood of a U.S. recession from 65 percent to about 50 percent,” Baumohl said in a report.
