A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which trace the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in open access.
The 47 million archival documents, stored over 27 km of linear in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were so far only available for a "humanitarian" purpose, that is, individually and in a nominative manner, at the request of a former victim or of her owners.
The eleven states in charge of their management - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will enable research “in particular on the displacement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the health status of forced workers,” says Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, opposed the opening to the public of these nominal documents because of the sensitivity of certain information.
Like supposed homosexuality or the mental disability of some victims of deportation.
The records of concentration camps or arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been gathered after the war for a practical purpose: to find civilians deported or subject to compulsory work and, possibly, to provide proof of their internment, in order to pave the way for compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees process tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest for some of the scientific community.
“There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents,” said Prof. Wolfgang Benz, director of the Centre for Research on Anti-Semitism at the Technische Universität Berlin in 2006.
