Congress approves the transposition of the Mifid, which entered into force on November 1
Alongside its parliamentary formality, which ended today with the vote of the Congress on the amendments incorporated into the draft Senate, the Government submitted to a public hearing the regulations to develop the new law, with the aim of entering into force before the end of the year.
Representatives of the various groups agreed to highlight the efforts made by MEPs and senators to negotiate and agree on the best regulations to ensure the protection of investors and to regulate in detail the activities of agencies so that markets function effectively.
The Mifid, which amends the Securities Market Act, involves modernizing the financial markets, while strengthening the protection of the investor, improving the powers of the leaders of the National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the different leaders of the European Union.
The new regulation will provide financial consulting services for specialized social reasons as well as to natural or legal persons and create a new type of financial services (ESIS), financial consulting companies (AFIs), which merge with securities companies, securities agencies and portfolio-managing companies.
Furthermore, it increases the number of systems for the execution of transactions on financial instruments, so that it is possible to add multilateral trading systems and order internationalization systems to regulated secondary markets, which face competition with current exchange managers.
The Act also requires investment firms to disclose in the market information on key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure, and forms of risk management, and requires them to keep a record of all transactions they perform, to facilitate oversight on the part of the CNMV.
Several amendments have been added through the Congressional Economics Commission, one of which highlights that securitized debts will be considered a "complex" financial instrument given its high risk to the investor, which has proven itself with what happened with the high-risk U.S. mortgage debt (subprime).
In addition, they took advantage of the management's transposition to legally define the functions that graduates in Economics may have 30 years after the royal decree was approved in 1977, which defines the professional functions reserved for economists.
For its part, the Senate has incorporated the creation of new figures in the financial sector, such as that of the Ombudsman, who will work on behalf of a company, who will not require the authorization of the CNMV and who will be able to lend its services to market products and attract new customers to different investment firms at the same time.
