What insurance is suitable for me?
Auto insurance, which covers the driver in the event of potential disasters, involves a significant expenditure that will depend on a variety of factors, such as age, gender, driver's license age, civil status, the type of vehicle to be insured or the use of it, among others.
Having a car is the main thing.
Choosing the right car insurance is even more difficult than choosing the vehicle model.
And that’s because choosing the right car insurance is even more difficult than choosing the model of the vehicle.
Car insurance is an agreement between an insurance company and the insurer.
This compromise is materialized in an insurance contract, which establishes that the company receives the value of the awarded premium and in exchange it becomes responsible for the obligation to pay compensation in the event of a disaster.
The premium is the insurance price, which takes into account various factors, such as age, gender, driving license age, civil status, the type of vehicle to be insured or the use of it, among others.
Insurance companies set their prices on the basis of statistics, so that the higher the chance of an accident, the higher the rating to be paid.
This is why people over 25 and women have to pay lower premiums, as statistics show that these people have a lower disaster rate due to their caution.
Similarly, using censuses, companies concluded that married people tend to have fewer accidents than single drivers.
The use of the vehicle will influence the frequency, and therefore the likelihood of an accident.
By increasing the frequency, the probabilities increase.
There are many variables that insurers take into account when establishing the premium price.
For this reason, the driver must study the situation thoroughly to choose the car insurance that best suits his/her profile.
Here we will expose the most significant variables when choosing one or the other type of insurance, so that this, in addition to adapting to the characteristics of the insurer, offers him a reasonable price.
Young people under the age of 25 must face various inconveniences when contracting insurance at an affordable price, such as the poor driving experience and driver’s license age.
Although the ideal for being well insured is risk-free insurance, other more economical options exist.
The most prospective drivers can opt for an all-risk insurance with frankness, so that they get insurance coverage at all-risk but at a more affordable price.
This form of agreement implies that the customer pays a portion of the amount of the claim.
“The portion of the amount of the claim that the customer pays will be determined according to the value of the premium, which will be higher the amount will be lower,” said Luis Noguera, the Spanish manager of First Europa, an online insurance mediator.
Another option is extended third-party insurance, so that the customer provides protection to deal with damage caused to third parties, but for those caused on their own car.
In addition, it would be covered against theft, fires and loss of the vehicle.
A counsel.
If you are under the age of 25 try to be cautious and avoid damages as far as possible, as this will impact on the bonus, which may reduce the insurance price in the future.
A bonus is a reduction in the base rate that the company owns.
On the contrary, a penalty is an increase in the basic tariff.
“Bonuses and sanctions will depend on the company and its profit.
If the company has had a good year, it will be able to afford to increase the bonuses," Noguera clarified.
Beyond the age of 25, it becomes easier for drivers to enter into an insurance contract, since the rate of claims is reduced thanks to the accumulated experience.
This is why it is best to choose an all-risk insurance with frankness.
"Normally young people can't take advantage of the experience previously acquired after an accident," said the director of the European company in Spain, adding that the majority of accidents occur during the second year of driving, once the 'fear of the novice' passed.
However, if the client is married but has no children yet, it is preferable that he negotiates insurance at all risks, as long as his economic situation allows him to do so.
Marriages with children are considered by insurers to be those with the lowest rate of claims, because the increases will be lower.
In this case the best insurance would be a free-of-risk insurance (which can be 300 euros), or an extended third-party insurance from the third year of the vehicle’s life when the insured has a high level of bonus.
“They have more casual driving and they have a greater purchasing power to afford the luxury of taking on a larger amount of franchises,” said Luis Noguera.
For retirees, free-of-risk insurance is preferable (which is 150 euros), or extended third-party insurance when the insurer has a high level of bonus.
It must be said that car insurance is something important, not only because it covers the driver in the face of possible disasters, but also because it represents an important expenditure, which is why it is essential to study the insurance that suits us most according to our personal situation.
