Venus is the infernal twin of the Earth.
Despite its hostile atmosphere to life, Venus looks more like the Earth than we thought so far: the European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered flashes in the atmosphere and wind turbulences at the poles, similar to those that appear in winter on Earth.
For nearly three decades, scientists have assumed that there are lightning flashes on Venus.
The European probe "Venus Express" today brought proof of this - it detected electromagnetic waves at the boundary of the atmosphere: lightning on Venus burst at a height of about 56 kilometers of cloud cloud, Christopher Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles reports in the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous cyprine theory, lightning would have revealed life on Earth: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
This is not the case on Venus: “If there was life, it must have been at a very ancient date in history,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
There should not be much living on the surface of Venus today: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, sometimes there are temperatures of 500 degrees.
“Venus may be the infernal twin of the Earth, but it remains a twin,” Russel said.
Why Venus, which resembles so much Earth in mass and dimensions, has been hit by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The departure of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important milestone in Venusian research, since no more probes were on the way to explore this planet since the 1980s.
According to the researchers, the most recent research results that have now been presented in several articles in "Nature" not only underline the singularity of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the commons with the Earth of our neighboring planet are more numerous than assumed at first.
Thus, the researchers found, in addition to the wind whirls already known at the North Pole, a cloud whirlwind at the South Pole, which rotates even faster.
The phenomenon recalls the currents of air in the terrestrial hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Astrophysics Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, is almost as large.
The planet called an evening or morning star revolves around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it turns much slower on itself: a Venusian day lasts 243 earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, hardly recalls the Earth, scientists assume that the two planets were formed under similar conditions.
On both, the water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but lost into space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide fixed on Earth in the form of carbonate, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
